related_questions.question: How much does it cost to go on an African safari hunt?
related_questions.title: AI Overview
list: Some countries, like South Africa, are known for offering more affordable hunting packages compared to countries like Tanzania or Botswana.
Plains game: . Opens in new tabHunting species like impala, kudu, and wildebeest is generally less expensive than hunting dangerous game like lions, leopards, or buffalo.
Trophy fees: . Opens in new tabEach animal has a specific trophy fee associated with it, which can significantly impact the overall cost. For example, a Cape buffalo hunt can cost upwards of $10,000.
Luxury lodges: High-end lodges and accommodations will increase the daily rate and overall cost.
Professional Hunter (PH): Hiring a PH for one-on-one guiding (1x1) is more expensive than having a PH for multiple hunters (2x1).
Observer costs: Non-hunting observers also incur daily rates and can add to the overall cost.
The longer the safari, the more you will pay for daily rates, accommodation, and other associated costs.
Travel to Africa: Flights to and from Africa can be a substantial expense.
Taxidermy: The cost of preparing and shipping trophies home can also add to the overall cost.
Rifle rental and ammunition: If you don't bring your own rifle, you'll need to factor in rental fees and the cost of ammunition.
Tips and gratuities: Tipping the PH, trackers, and other staff is customary.

Budget-friendly plains game package: . Opens in new tabA 7-day, 3-animal package in South Africa can be found for around $3,175, including trophy fees and a free observer, according to Discount African Hunts.
More comprehensive plains game hunt: . Opens in new tabA 12-day hunt for 12 animals in South Africa can be found for $12,900, including all trophy fees, accommodation, and meals.
Dangerous game hunt: . Opens in new tabA 21-day full bag safari in Tanzania, including leopard, lion, and Cape buffalo, can cost upwards of $69,000, according to Discount African Hunts.
